{"title_page": "J Balvin", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2020}}\n{{short description|Colombian reggaeton singer}}\n{{Spanish name|Osorio|Balv\u00edn}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name             = J Balvin\n| image            = J Balvin - Ay Vamos - Festival de Vi\u00f1a del Mar 2017 (4).jpg\n| caption          = J Balvin performing in 2017\n| background       = solo_singer<!--INCLUDES rap artists-->\n| birth_name       = Jos\u00e9 \u00c1lvaro Osorio Balv\u00edn\n| birth_date       = {{birth date and age|mf=yes|1985|5|7}}\n| birth_place      = [[Medell\u00edn]], Colombia\n| genre            = {{hlist|[[Reggaeton]]|[[Latin pop]]|[[Urbano music|urbano]]|[[Hip hop music|hip hop]]}}\n| occupation       = Singer\n| instrument       = {{flatlist|\n* Vocals\n* guitar\n}}\n| years_active     = 2004\u2013present\n| label            = {{hlist|[[Capitol Latin]]|[[Universal Music Group|Universal]]|Infinity}}\n| associated_acts  = {{hlist|[[Bad Bunny]]|[[Ozuna (singer)|Ozuna]]|[[Anitta (singer)|Anitta]]}}\n| website          = {{URL|jbalvin.com}}\n}}\n'''Jos\u00e9 \u00c1lvaro Osorio Balv\u00edn''' (born May 7, 1985) is a Colombian [[reggaeton]] singer. Balvin was born in [[Medell\u00edn]], Colombia.<ref>[http://www.cromos.com.co/personajes/actualidad/articulo-143587-j-balvin-el-trono-del-reggaeton J. Balvin \u00a1100 % Reggueton!] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160404200633/http://www.cromos.com.co/personajes/actualidad/articulo-143587-j-balvin-el-trono-del-reggaeton |date=April 4, 2016 }} Viernes 9 de marzo de 2012</ref> At age 17, he moved to the United States. He moved to [[Oklahoma]] and [[New York (state)|New York]] to learn English. He then returned to Medell\u00edn and gained popularity performing at clubs in the city. He [[List of awards and nominations received by J Balvin|has won]] five [[Billboard Latin Music Awards]], four [[Latin Grammy Awards]], two [[MTV Video Music Awards]] and four [[Latin American Music Awards]] and received two [[Grammy Award]] nominations. In 2017 the [[BMI Awards|BMI Latin Awards]] named him the Contemporary Latin Songwriter of the Year for his contribution in latin music industry.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/latin/8256056/bmi-latin-awards-winners|title=BMI Latin Awards Honor Luis Fonsi, Residente, Horacio Palencia, J Balvin & Sony ATV|website=Billboard|access-date=November 20, 2019}}</ref> He became the first Latino artist to be a [[Lollapalooza]] headliner.\n\nHis breakthrough came in 2014 with the single \"[[6 AM]]\" featuring Puerto Rican singer [[Farruko]] which peaked at number 2 on the ''Billboard'' Hot Latin Songs chart. In 2016, he released ''[[Energia (album)|Energia]]'', which included the hit singles \"[[Ginza (song)|Ginza]]\", \"[[Bobo (J Balvin song)|Bobo]]\", \"[[Safari (J Balvin song)|Safari]]\", and \"Sigo Extra\u00f1\u00e1ndote\". In June 2017, J Balvin released the single \"[[Mi Gente (J Balvin and Willy William song)|Mi Gente]]\" with [[Willy William]]. On August 1, 2017, \"Mi Gente\" topped the Global Top 50 on [[Spotify]], and later reached one billion views on [[YouTube]]. In January 2018, he released the hit single \"[[Machika]]\" featuring Jeon and [[Anitta (singer)|Anitta]]. He collaborated with [[Cardi B]] and [[Bad Bunny]] on the US [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] number-one single \"[[I Like It (Cardi B, Bad Bunny and J Balvin song)|I Like It]]\", which was also nominated for the [[Grammy Award for Record of the Year]].\n\nThough his music is primarily reggaeton, J Balvin has experimented with a variety of musical genres in his work, including electronica, house music, trap, and R&B. His original musical inspirations included rock groups such as [[Metallica]] and [[Nirvana (band)|Nirvana]], and reggaeton artist [[Daddy Yankee]]. He has collaborated with [[Latin Americans|Latin American]] artists such as [[Ozuna (singer)|Ozuna]], [[Anitta (singer)|Anitta]], [[Nicky Jam]], [[Alejandro Sanz]], and [[Pitbull (rapper)|Pitbull]]. Despite working with many English-speaking artists such as  [[Beyonc\u00e9]], [[Pharrell Williams]], [[The Black Eyed Peas]], [[Cardi B]] and [[Major Lazer]], J Balvin continues to sing almost exclusively in Spanish, and hopes to introduce Spanish-language music to a global audience. He is also noted for his eclectic and colorful fashion sense.\n\n==Life and career==\n\n=== 1985\u20132013: Early life and career beginnings ===\nJ Balvin was born into a middle-class family in Medell\u00edn, Colombia on May 7, 1985.<ref name=\"mission\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/07/06/arts/music/j-balvin-energia-interview.html|title=J Balvin Is a Man With a Mission: Making Reggaeton Global|last=Coscarelli|first=Joe|date=July 5, 2016|work=New York Times|accessdate=March 30, 2018}}</ref> His father was an economist and business owner, and he grew up in a large home in the hills outside the city.<ref name=fader>{{cite web|url=http://www.thefader.com/2016/02/09/j-balvin-cover-story-interview|title=For J Balvin, Dignity is Not Negotiable|last=Bishop|first=Marlon|date=February 6, 2017|accessdate=March 30, 2018|work=[[The Fader]]|publisher=Andy Cohn}}</ref> He grew up listening to [[rock music|rock]] groups such as [[Metallica]] and [[Nirvana (band)|Nirvana]], and states that he incorporates the [[grunge]] aesthetic into his personal style, having a Nirvana tattoo on his knee.<ref name=nirvana>{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/features/reggaeton-star-j-balvin-on-nirvana-pharrell-guinness-honor-w471873|title=Reggaeton Ambassador J Balvin Talks Nirvana, Pharrell, Guinness Record|work=Rolling Stone|date=March 16, 2017|accessdate=March 30, 2018}}</ref> He developed an interest in reggaeton after listening to [[Daddy Yankee]]. He recalls that \u201cI was such a fan that I was copying his style, the way he moved onstage, his flows, his raps,\" comparing him to the reggaeton equivalent of [[Jay-Z]].<ref name=\"mission\"/> His father's business went bankrupt, and the family lost their home and car, requiring the family to move to a poorer neighborhood. On this period of his life, J Balvin notes, \u201cWhen I would go to the barrio, people saw me as a rich person, but when I\u2019m around rich people they see me as someone from the ghetto. It\u2019s all perceptions. I like moving between worlds. I feel equally comfortable in both.\u201d<ref name=fader/>\n\nWhen J Balvin was 16, he participated in an English-exchange program in [[Oklahoma]], but was disappointed by the experience, saying, \u201cI was expecting the U.S. that everyone knows from [[Hollywood]].\"<ref name=\"mission\"/> Soon after the program, he moved to [[New York City]] to further study English and music, living with an aunt on [[Staten Island]] and working as a dog walker.<ref name=fader/> During his time in New York, he became fascinated by the business savvy of New York rappers [[50 Cent]] and [[P. Diddy]].<ref name=\"mission\"/> J Balvin worked various jobs in New York, Miami, and Medell\u00edn, including working illegally in the United States as a roofer and house painter.<ref name=\"mission\"/> He ultimately decided to return to Colombia and began performing at various urban clubs in Medell\u00edn and increasing his social media following. He enrolled at the prestigious [[EAFIT University]] in Medell\u00edn for seven semesters, studying international business.<ref name=agridulce>{{cite web|url=https://www.elespectador.com/noticias/investigacion/el-grammy-agridulce-de-j-balvin-articulo-600614|title=El Grammy agridulce de J Balvin|work=El Espectador|last=Quevedo Hern\u00e1ndez|first=Norbey|date=November 21, 2015|accessdate=March 30, 2015|language=es}}</ref> At age 19, he began to seriously pursue a career in music and adopted the stage name J Balvin \u201cEl Negocio\", meaning \"The Business\" in English.<ref name=fader/>\n\nHe met his DJ and business partner David Rivera Mazo in a freestyle battle on the street in Medell\u00edn.<ref name=fader/> The two became fast friends and started producing and promoting their own music without a record label. J Balvin's early songs were described as \"basically poor imitations of commercial reggaeton from Puerto Rico,\" but he soon adopted a more relaxed, minimalist style in his music.<ref name=fader/> He signed to EMI Colombia in 2009 and soon after released the single \"Ella Me Cautiv\u00f3,\" which charted at number 35 on the ''Billboard'' [[Tropical Songs]] chart.<ref name=allmusicbio>{{cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/artist/j-balvin-mn0002385504/biography|title=J Balvin - Allmusic Biography|last=Jurek|first=Thom|accessdate=March 30, 2018}}</ref> He released his debut album, ''Real'', in 2009.<ref name=\"pharrell\">{{cite web|url=http://www.xxlmag.com/news/2017/02/j-balvin-interview-pharrell/|title=J BALVIN\u2019S HIP-HOP CONNECTION INCLUDES LIFE ADVICE FROM PHARRELL|work=[[XXL (magazine)|XXL]]|publisher=Townsquare Media|last=Krastz|first=Roger|date=February 10, 2017}}</ref> In 2012, J Balvin released a mixtape featuring many of his early hits in Colombia, including \"En Lo Oscuro\" and \"Como un Animal.\" His first international hit was the one-night-stand-themed \"Yo Te Lo Dije\", and signed with Universal subsidiary Capitol Latin a year later.<ref name=fader/>\n\n=== 2014\u201316: \"6AM\" success and ''La Familia'' ===\n[[File:Lesin valencia junto j balvin (cropped).JPG|thumb|left|J Balvin in June 2014]]\nIn February 2014, J Balvin released a new track entitled \"[[6 AM]],\" featuring Puerto Rican singer [[Farruko]]. J Balvin described the lyrical content of the song as the \"Latin version of ''[[The Hangover]]'',\" where the two singers attempt to remember what happened during a night of partying.<ref name=farruko6am>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/events/year-in-music-2014/6405612/j-balvin-farruko-on-6-am-number-one-charts-2014|title=J Balvin on His No. 1 Hit '6 AM' Being the 'Latin Version' of 'The Hangover'|work=Billboard|publisher=Prometheus Global Media|date=December 12, 2014|accessdate=March 30, 2018}}</ref> The song debuted at number 43 on the ''Billboard'' Latin Airplay chart in February and reached number one in May.<ref name=farruko6am/> His album ''La Familia'' reached number ten on the ''Billboard'' Top Latin Albums chart, spending 122 weeks on the chart in total.<ref name=lafamiliachart>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/music/j-balvin/chart-history/latin-albums/song/803617|title=J Balvin - La Familia Chart History|work=Billboard|publisher=Prometheus Global Media|accessdate=May 15, 2018}}</ref>\n\nShortly after, J Balvin released his second track in the United States, \"[[Ay Vamos]],\" which solidified his mark in the Latin urban market.<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web|url=http://latino.foxnews.com/latino/entertainment/2015/06/25/colombian-singer-j-balvin-cancels-miss-usa-appearance-over-donald-trumps-mexico/|title=Colombian singer cancels Miss USA appearance over Donald Trump\u2019s comments|work=[[Fox News Latino]]|accessdate=June 25, 2015}}</ref> It won a Latin Grammy Award for Best Urban Song.<ref name=allmusicbio/> This was a bonus track on the deluxe edition of J Balvin's album ''La Familia B-Sides'' The music video is one of the most watched Latin music videos of all time, at over one billion views. The song went to number one on the ''Billboard'' Hot Latin Songs chart in 2015. The remix, featuring Nicky Jam and [[French Montana]] was used in the soundtrack to the film ''[[Furious 7]]''. J Balvin performed the track at the 2015 Premios Lo Nuestro and the ''Billboard'' Latin Music Awards. J  Balvin has been featured on remixes of \"Sorry\" by [[Justin Bieber]], \"The Way\" and \"Problem\" by [[Ariana Grande]], \"Blurred Lines\" by [[Robin Thicke]], \"Maps\" by [[Maroon 5]], and \"Stuck on a Feeling\" by [[Prince Royce]].<ref name=\"auto\"/> J Balvin was the first Colombian singer to record with \"The Prince of Bachata\" and establishing itself as an international artist.<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\nJ Balvin swept the urban category at the 2015 [[Premios Lo Nuestro]], including \"Urban Artist of the Year,\" \"Urban Album of the Year,\" \"Urban Song of the Year\" and \"Urban Collaboration of the Year.\" On February 12, the nominees for the [[Billboard Latin Music Awards|''Billboard'' Latin Music Awards]] were announced, and J Balvin was nominated 13 times, of these nominations, eight were in the same category twice \"Ay Vamos\" and \"6 AM,\" being the most nominated Colombian and the first urban artist from Colombia. J Balvin won New Artist, Latin Rhythm Song of the Year, and Latin Rhythm Song Artist of the Year, where he dedicated the award to his home country of Colombia.<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n[[File:J Balvin 2015.jpg|thumb|Balvin performing in 2015]]\nIn June 2015, it was announced that J Balvin had cancelled his performance on [[Miss USA 2015]] to protest [[Donald Trump]]'s inflammatory comments insulting illegal immigrants,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/latin/6605876/j-balvin-cancels-miss-usa-performance-donald-trump-latin-comments|title=J Balvin Cancels Miss USA Performance After Donald Trump's Comments on illegal immigrants: Exclusive|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|accessdate=June 25, 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"auto\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.people.com/article/j-balvin-cancels-miss-usa-performance-donald-trumps-comments-mexicans|title=J Balvin Cancels Miss USA Performance After Donald Trump Comments About Illegal Immigrants : People.com|work=[[People (magazine)|People]]|accessdate=June 25, 2015}}</ref> saying, \"During [Trump's] [[Donald Trump presidential campaign, 2016|presidential campaign kickoff speech last week]] [June 2015], Trump accused illegal immigrants of bringing drugs, crime and rapists to the U.S.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.latintimes.com/miss-usa-2015-show-j-balvin-cancels-appearance-following-donald-trumps-comments-324822|title=Miss USA 2015 Show: J Balvin Cancels Appearance Following Donald Trump's Comments On Latinos|author=Armando Tinoco|date=June 25, 2015|work=[[Latin Times]]|accessdate=June 25, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wafb.com/story/29402543/j-balvin-cancels-miss-usa-appearance-over-trumps-comments|title=J Balvin cancels Miss USA appearance over Trump's comments|date=June 24, 2015|work=[[Associated Press]] via [[WAFB]]|accessdate=June 25, 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150626144333/http://www.wafb.com/story/29402543/j-balvin-cancels-miss-usa-appearance-over-trumps-comments|archivedate=June 26, 2015}}</ref> His live performance had been scheduled for July 12, 2015 in [[Louisiana]], which would have been J Balvin's first performance on national mainstream television.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/latin/6605876/j-balvin-cancels-miss-usa-performance-donald-trump-latin-comments|title=J Balvin Cancels Miss USA Performance After Donald Trump's Comments on Latins: Exclusive|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|accessdate=June 25, 2015}}</ref>\n\n=== 2016\u201317: ''Energia'' ===\nOn January 16, 2016, J Balvin premiered his new single \"Ginza\" from his upcoming album, at the Premios Juventud. Later that week, he premiered the music video on Vevo. The music video broke the record for the most views for a Latin music video in the first 24 hours, at over two million views. Since then, the video has racked up over 807 million views.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=zZjSX01P5dE|title=YouTube Ginza video count|last=|first=|date=|website=|publisher=[[YouTube]]|access-date=}}</ref> The song reached number one on ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]''{{'}}s [[Hot Latin Songs]] chart for the week of October 17, 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/charts/latin-songs|title=Latin Music: Top Latin Songs|website=Billboard.com}}</ref> The song also set a new [[Guinness World Record]] for the longest stay at number one on the chart.<ref name=nirvana/> J Balvin became the first artist to receive a [[RIAA certification|diamond]] certification in the Latin field from the RIAA, denoting digital sales of 600,000 units for his songs \"6 AM\" and \"Ay Vamos.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=J Balvin Earns First-Ever RIAA Latin Digital Diamond Honor|url=https://www.riaa.com/newsitem.php?content_selector=riaa-news-gold-and-platinum&news_month_filter=10&news_year_filter=2015&id=6BC000B7-6D8B-5E62-7931-D65D5736F813|publisher=RIAA|accessdate=October 27, 2015|date=October 26, 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151027214158/http://www.riaa.com/newsitem.php?content_selector=riaa-news-gold-and-platinum&news_month_filter=10&news_year_filter=2015&id=6BC000B7-6D8B-5E62-7931-D65D5736F813|archivedate=October 27, 2015}}</ref> Andrew Casillas of ''Rolling Stone'' wrote that \"with its deliciously liquid beat, [\"Ginza\"] among the finest three minutes in reggaet\u00f3n history.\"<ref name=Energiarollingstone>{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/lists/10-best-latin-albums-of-2016-w458207/j-balvin-energia-w458211|title=J Balvin - ''Energia'': 10 Best Latin Albums of 2016|last=Casillas|first=Andrew|date=December 30, 2016|accessdate=March 30, 2018|work=Rolling Stone}}</ref>\n\nOn June 24, 2016, J Balvin released his fourth studio album ''[[Energia (album)|Energia]]''. ''Energia'' debuted at number one on the ''Billboard'' Top Latin Albums chart, signifying his first time topping that chart.<ref name=energiabow>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/biz/articles/7430971/j-balvins-energia-bows-at-no-1-on-top-latin-albums|title=J Balvin's 'Energia' Bows at No. 1 on Top Latin Albums|work=Billboard|last=Mendizabal|first=Amaya|date=July 7, 2016|accessdate=April 27, 2018}}</ref> It had the third-best debut sales of any Latin artist in 2016, after [[Juan Gabriel]]'s ''Los Duo 2'' and [[Banda MS|Banda Sinaloense MS de Sergio Lizarraga]]'s ''Que Bendicion''. It also debuted at number 38 on the all-genre ''Billboard'' 200.<ref name=energiabow/> The album featured collaborations with Daddy Yankee, [[Juanes]], [[Pharrell]], and [[Yandel]].<ref name=didntknowenergia>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/latin/7415687/j-balvins-new-album-energia|title=7 Things You Didn't Know About J Balvin's New Album 'Energia'|work=Billboard|last=Fernandez|first=Suzette|date=June 23, 2016|accessdate=April 27, 2018}}</ref> He launched 3 hit singles from the album, \"Bobo,\" \"Safari,\" and \"Sigo Extranandote,\" which all reached the top 10 of the Latin charts.  \"Bobo\" spent a week at the top of the ''Billboard'' Hot Latin Songs chart.<ref name=energiabow/> Mario Prunes of Allmusic described ''Energia'' as \"an album that knew it was going to be an international blockbuster almost a year before its release,\" due to the success of \"Ginza\".<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.allmusic.com/album/energia-mw0002952969|title= Review: J Balvin - Energia|work= Allmusic|accessdate=April 19, 2018|last=Prunes|first=Mario}}</ref> ''Rolling Stone'' ranked the album number four on the magazine's list of the 10 Best Latin Albums of 2016.<ref name=Energiarollingstone/>\n\n[[File:J Balvin - Sigo Extra\u00f1\u00e1ndote - Festival de Vi\u00f1a del Mar 2017 (2).jpg|thumb|J Balvin performing \"Sigo Extra\u00f1\u00e1ndote\" in Chile in March 2017|alt=|left]]\n\nIn promotion of the album, J Balvin embarked on the ''Energia'' Tour, traveling with several special guests including [[French Montana]], [[Zion & Lennox]], [[Bad Bunny]], and [[Steve Aoki]], the latter of which appeared as a surprise for fans during the last stop of the tour in [[Miami]].<ref name=energiaaoki>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/latin/7998695/j-balvin-energia-tour-finale|title=J Balvin Brings Out Steve Aoki for Energia Tour Finale in Miami|work=Billboard|last=Fernandez|first=Suzette|date=October 14, 2017|accessdate=April 27, 2018}}</ref> That same year, J Balvin featured on \"Cuando Seas Grande\" by Spanish musician [[Alejandro Sanz]] and American singer [[Sofia Carson]]\u00b4s \"Love is the Name.\"<ref name=allmusicbio/> He launched a partnership with SoundCloud and Buchanan's Whiskey in a project called Es Nuestro Momento, where fans can access J Balvin's previously unreleased a capella vocals and create personalized remixes of his songs.<ref name=forbes>{{cite web|url= https://www.forbes.com/sites/hughmcintyre/2017/03/13/j-balvin-explains-why-his-spanish-language-music-does-so-well-in-america/#1bdc711160a5|title=J. Balvin Explains Why His Spanish-Language Music Does So Well In America|work=Forbes|publisher=Forbes Media, LLC.|last=McIntyre|first=Hugh|date=March 13, 2017|accessdate=March 30, 2018}}</ref> Buchanan's Whisky also served as a sponsor for the ''Energia'' Tour in honor of Hispanic Heritage Month.<ref name=energiaaoki/>\n\n=== 2017\u20132018: International success: \"Mi Gente\" & ''Vibras'' ===\nOn June 30, 2017, J Balvin released his new single along with the official music video \"[[Mi Gente (J Balvin and Willy William song)|Mi Gente]]\" featuring [[Willy William]]. On August 1, 2017, \"Mi Gente\" became the number 1 song in the world according to Global Top 50 on [[Spotify]]. It soon reached 1 billion views on [[YouTube]]. In September 2017, the song was remixed with American artist [[Beyonc\u00e9]].<ref name=livemoment>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/8023274/j-balvin-lives-his-moment-with-chart-and-touring-success|title=J Balvin Lives His Moment With Chart And Touring Success|last=Estevez|first=Marjua|date=November 8, 2017|accessdate=April 19, 2018|work=Billboard|publisher=Prometheus Global Media}}</ref> The remix reached #3 in the United States, giving Balvin his first USA top ten single. J Balvin and Willy William released six more \"Mi Gente\" remixes with [[Steve Aoki]], [[Alesso]], [[Cedric Gervais]], [[Dillon Francis]], [[Sunnery James & Ryan Marciano]], and Henry Fong.<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/latin/8006819/j-balvin-mi-gente-remixes-steve-aoki-cedric-gervais-dillon-francis|title= J Balvin Drops Six New 'Mi Gente' Remixes With Steve Aoki, Cedric Gervais, Dillon Francis & More|work= billboard.com|accessdate=October 25, 2017}}</ref> Despite the song's success, \"Mi Gente\" did not win any awards at the 2017 Latin Grammy Awards, with many awards going to [[Luis Fonsi]]'s hit \"[[Despacito]]\".<ref name=bestjbalvin>{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/pictures/latin-grammys-2017-luis-fonsi-residente-win-big-w512064/best-j-balvin-brings-global-starpower-to-the-stage-w512092|title=J Balvin brings global starpower to the stage|last=Raygoza|first=Isabela|date=November 17, 2017|accessdate=March 30, 2018|work=Rolling Stone}}</ref> At the ceremony, he performed \"Mi Gente\" as well as \"Si Tu Novio Te Deja Sola\" alongside [[Bad Bunny]] and his remix of \"[[Unforgettable (French Montana song)|Unforgettable]]\" with [[French Montana]].<ref name=bestjbalvin/>\n\nOn January 19, 2018, J Balvin released his new single along with the official music video \"Machika\" featuring Jeon and [[Anitta]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Marjua|first1=Estevez|title=J Balvin, Anitta & Jeon Are War-Ready in 'Machika' Premiere: Watch|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/latin/8095054/j-balvin-anitta-jeon-machika-premiere|website=Billboard|publisher=Billboard|accessdate=January 19, 2018}}</ref> His collaboration with Nicky Jam, \"X,\" was released on March 1, 2018 and the music video received 288 million views on YouTube in less than a month.<ref name=xnyt>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/aponline/2018/03/26/arts/ap-us-music-nicky-jam.html|title=Nicky Jam's Friendship With J Balvin Produces a New Hit: 'X'|work=New York Times|date=March 26, 2018|accessdate=March 30, 2018|publisher=A.G. Sulzberger}}</ref> Nicky Jam stated that he attributes the success of \"X\" to J Balvin's contribution.<ref name=xnyt/> He also appeared on [[Cardi B]]\u00b4s ''[[Invasion of Privacy (album)|Invasion of Privacy]]'' album, with Bad Bunny on the song \"I Like It.\"<ref name=allmusicbio/> It became Balvin's first number one single on the US [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]].<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/8463605/cardi-b-i-like-it-hot-100-number-one-j-balvin-bad-bunny |title=Cardi B Becomes First Female Rapper With Two Billboard Hot 100 No. 1s, as 'I Like It,' With Bad Bunny & J Balvin, Follows 'Bodak Yellow' to the Top |last=Trust |first=Gary |date=July 2, 2018 |work=Billboard |accessdate=July 2, 2018}}</ref>\n\nJ Balvin released the album ''[[Vibras]]'' on May 25, 2018.<ref name=vibrasinsta>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/latin/8299811/j-balvin-new-album-vibras|title=J Balvin Sets Release Date for New Album 'Vibras'|last=Fernandez|first=Suzette|date=April 9, 2018|accessdate=April 19, 2018|work=Billboard|publisher=Prometheus Global Media}}</ref> The two lead singles from the album were \u201cMachika\u201d and \u201cAhora.\u201d<ref name=vibrasinsta/> On April 23, 2018, J Balvin announced the dates for his Vibras tour revealing the 27 cities where he will be [[Performance|performing]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/j-balvin-plots-north-american-vibras-tour-w519448|title=J Balvin Plots North American 'Vibras' Tour|work=Rolling Stone|access-date=April 26, 2018}}</ref> ''Vibras'' claimed the record for the most-streamed Latin album in 24 hours on the streaming platform for 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/latin/8459722/j-balvin-vibras-apple-music-record|title=J Balvin's 'Vibras' Album Has Biggest First Week Ever for a Latin Artist on Apple Music|work=Billboard|last=Fernandez|first=Suzette|date=6 June 2018|accessdate=7 June 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180608201248/https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/latin/8459722/j-balvin-vibras-apple-music-record|archive-date=8 June 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> In the United States, it debuted at number one on the [[Top Latin Albums]] chart for the issue dated 9 June 2018. According to [[Nielsen SoundScan|Nielsen Music]], the record sold 22,000 [[album-equivalent units]] and became Balvin's second number-one album on the chart, following ''Energia'' in 2016. Additionally, ''Vibras'' scored the largest streaming week ever for a Latin album by an artist; its songs were streamed 16.1&nbsp;million times.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/8459608/j-balvin-vibras-no-1-top-latin-albums|title=J Balvin Lands Biggest Week of 2018 For a Latin Album With No. 1 Debut of 'Vibras'|work=Billboard|last=Bustios|first=Pamela|date=6 June 2018|accessdate=6 June 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180608085812/https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/8459608/j-balvin-vibras-no-1-top-latin-albums|archive-date=8 June 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> Subsequently, it debuted at number 15 on the US [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]] and became his highest-charting album on the chart.<ref name=\"200peak\"/> \n\nIn an interview with Ebro Darden for Beats 1 Radio on [[Apple Music]] in April 2018, Balvin described the sound of the record as 33% [[dancehall]], 33% [[Contemporary R&B|R&B]], and 33% reggaeton. Balvin further elaborated that a lot of love was put into the album's work and that contains different vibes, hence the name, ''Vibras'', \"The real meaning of this album was what's going on with Spanish music that's going so global, the fact that we did an album that the beats are so amazing that you don't have to understand what we say, you just have to love the songs.\"<ref name=\"complexinterview\">{{cite web|url=http://www.complex.com/music/2018/05/j-balvin-new-album-vibras-is-here|title=J Balvin's New Album 'Vibras' Is Here|work=[[Complex (magazine)|Complex]]|last=Pimentel|first=Julia|date=25 May 2018|accessdate=25 May 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180525213803/http://www.complex.com/music/2018/05/j-balvin-new-album-vibras-is-here|archive-date=25 May 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== 2019\u2013present: ''Oasis'' and ''Colores''===\n[[File:Bad Bunny 2019 by Glenn Francis.jpg|thumb|170px|J Balvin released the 2019 album ''Oasis'' in collaboration with Puerto Rican rapper [[Bad Bunny]] (pictured)]]\nOn June 27, 2019, J Balvin released his new album in collaboration with Bad Bunny titled ''[[Oasis (J Balvin and Bad Bunny album)|Oasis]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-latin/j-balvin-bad-bunny-oasis-joint-album-852950/|title=J Balvin, Bad Bunny Continue Can\u2019t-Miss Run With Joint Album \u2018Oasis\u2019|last=Leight|first=Elias|date=June 28, 2019|website=Rolling Stone|language=en-US|access-date=June 28, 2019}}</ref> The record was released overnight and was deemed a \"surprise\" release.<ref name=nytimesoasis>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/06/28/arts/music/bad-bunny-j-balvin-oasis.html|last=Coscarelli|first=Joe|title=How J Balvin and Bad Bunny Made Their Surprise Album, \u2018Oasis\u2019\n|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=June 28, 2019|accessdate=November 26, 2019}}</ref> The two artists first met at a J Balvin concert in Puerto Rico, when Bad Bunny was working on releasing music on SoundCloud, and then collaborated on the 2017 track \u201cSi Tu Novio Te Deja Sola\u201d. The chemistry between the two was so strong that they came up with the idea to release a joint album.<ref name=nytimesoasis/> ''Oasis'' peaked at number nine on the ''Billboard'' Hot 100<ref name=oasishot100>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/music/J-Balvin/chart-history/billboard-200|title=J Balvin Chart History|work=Billboard|publisher=Prometheus Global Media|accessdate=November 26, 2019}}</ref> and topped the ''Billboard'' US Latin Albums chart.<ref name=oasislatinalbums>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/music/J-Balvin/chart-history/latin-albums|title=J Balvin US Latin Albums Chart|work=Billboard|publisher=Prometheus Global Media|accessdate=November 26, 2019}}</ref> The album was nominated for Best Latin Rock, Urban or Alternative Album at the [[62nd Annual Grammy Awards|2020 Grammy Awards]] and was named one of ''Rolling Stone''\u2018s Best Latin Albums of 2019.<ref name=bloody>{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-latin/j-balvin-rojo-video-colores-track-list-957599/|title=J Balvin Gets Bloody in Haunting New \u2018Rojo\u2019 Video|last=Exposito|first=Suzy|work=Rolling Stone|date=February 27, 2020|accessdate=March 25, 2020}}</ref>\n\nHis collaboration with Spanish singer [[Rosal\u00eda (singer)|Rosal\u00eda]] \"[[Con altura]]\" won Best Urban Song at the [[20th Annual Latin Grammy Awards|2019 Latin Grammy Awards]].<ref name=blancoRS>{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/j-balvin-blanco-music-video-913121/|title= Watch J Balvin\u2019s Futuristic Music Video for \u2018Blanco\u2019\n|last=Zemler|first=Emily|date=November 15, 2019|accessdate=March 25, 2020|work=Rolling Stone}}</ref> The song received positive reviews from critics and ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' ranked it 5th on their list of 100 Best Songs of 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/list/8545893/best-songs-of-2019-top-100|title=The 100 Best Songs of 2019: Staff List|website=Billboard|access-date=2019-12-30}}</ref> J Balvin was a guest performer in the [[Super Bowl LIV halftime show]] headlined by [[Jennifer Lopez]] and [[Shakira]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Bajuder |first1=David |title=Jennifer Lopez, Shakira in joyful, exuberant Super Bowl LIV halftime show |url=https://www.denverpost.com/2020/02/02/jennifer-lopez-shakira-super-bowl-liv-halftime-show-review/ |publisher=The Denver Post |agency=The Associated Press |accessdate=3 February 2020 |date=3 February 2020}}</ref> He also collaborated with [[Major Lazer]] and Dominican dembow singer [[El Alfa]] on the single \"[[Que Calor]]\" in September 2019.<ref name=blancoRS/> \n\nIn November 2019, J Balvin released the music video for the single \"Blanco\", which introduced a \"futuristic, all-white environment filled with hypnotic dancers and flying cats\".<ref name=blancoRS/> On March 20, 2020, J Balvin released the album ''[[Colores]]'', in which every song is named after a color except the song \"Arco\u00edris\" (the Spanish word for rainbow).<ref name=coloresguardian>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2020/mar/22/j-balvin-colores-review-reggaeton-hooks-ideas|title=J Balvin: Colores review \u2013 a riot of hooks and ideas|work=The Guardian|last=Cragg|first=Michael|date=March 22, 2020|accessdate=March 24, 2020}}</ref><ref name=coloresguardian2>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2020/mar/19/j-balvin-colores-review|title=J Balvin: Colores review \u2013 with this much style, who needs substance?|work=The Guardian|last=Petridis|first=Alexis|date=March 19, 2020|accessdate=March 24, 2020}}</ref> The album contains influences from dancehall, R&B, and electronica, and features Nigerian [[afrobeats]] artist [[Mr Eazi]] on the song \"Arco\u00edris\".<ref name=coloresguardian/><ref name=coloresguardian2/> Suzy Exposito of ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' called the album \"sophisticated show of Balvin\u2019s sonic palette\".<ref name=RScolores>{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-album-reviews/j-balvin-colores-969836/|title=J Balvin Nuances His Cosmopolitan Reggaeton Sound on \u2018Colores\u2019|date=March 20, 2020|accessdate=March 24, 2020|work=Rolling Stone|publisher=Jann Wenner}}</ref> The album artwork was created by Japanese artist [[Takashi Murakami]].<ref name=coloresguardian2/> Balvin collaborated with Murakami for the music videos and album and single artwork, which notably feature Murakami's flowers, as well as American clothing brand [[Guess (clothing)|Guess]] on a [[capsule collection]] inspired by the album.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.highsnobiety.com/p/guess-j-balvin-spring-2020/|title=J Balvin's New GUESS Collection Is Inspired by His Upcoming Album|website=[[Highsnobiety]]|last=Sawyer|first=Jonathan|date=26 February 2020|accessdate=28 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Artistry==\n===Musical style===\nCritics have contrasted J Balvin's musical style from the first internationally popular wave of reggaeton led by Daddy Yankee. Marlon Bishop of ''The Fader'' described his vocal delivery as a \"gentle drawl\", differing greatly from the rapid-fire, aggressive delivery of earlier reggaeton acts.<ref name=fader/> He generally sings over his beats as opposed to rapping, and favors a more melodic, pop-influenced style.<ref name=hotagain>{{cite web|url=http://www.thefader.com/2015/11/23/j-balvin-reggaeton-interview|title=How J Balvin Made Reggaeton Hot Again|last=Bishop|first=Marlon|work=The Fader|date=November 23, 2015|accessdate=March 30, 2018}}</ref> Describing his music's production, Bishop writes, \"Instead of the hard-edged, maximalist beats of the first wave, Balvin\u2019s tracks are moody and spaced out\".<ref name=fader/>  He frequently works with Medellin-based writer/producers Alejandro \u201cSky\u201d Ramirez and Carlo Alejandro \u201cMosty\u201d Pati\u00f1o, whom he often name-drops in his songs.<ref name=medellinexports>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/magazine-feature/7693380/medellin-latin-stars-maluma-j-balvin|title=Medellin's Musical Exports: Maluma, J Balvin & More Stars the Colombian City Spawned|last=Cobo|first=Leila|date=February 16, 2017|work=Billboard|publisher=Prometheus Global Media}}</ref> He has been credited with popularizing a new style of reggaeton based in Medellin, along with [[Maluma (singer)|Maluma]] and Puerto Ricans who have relocated to the city to become involved in the reggaeton scene, such as Nicky Jam and Farruko.<ref name=hotagain/>\n\n{{multiple image\n| footer = In addition to the primary inspiration of Daddy Yankee, J Balvin has cited both salsa musician [[H\u00e9ctor Lavoe]] (''left'') and rapper [[Snoop Dogg]] (''right'') as influential for him and his music\n| image1 = El Cantante.jpg\n| width1 = 216\n| alt1 = H\u00e9ctor Lavoe in an undated photo\n| image2 = Snoop Dogg 2012.jpg\n| width2 = 146\n| alt2 = Snoop Dogg with a beanie in a white collared shirt\n| align = right}}\n\nThough he cites Daddy Yankee as his biggest musical inspiration, J Balvin's earliest influences were rock bands such as Metallica and Nirvana, as well as salsa legend [[Hector Lavoe]].<ref name=nirvana/> He has covered Nirvana's hit \"[[Smells Like Teen Spirit]]\" in live performances.<ref name=nirvana/> As a teenager, he listened to hip-hop artists such as [[2Pac]], [[The Notorious B.I.G.]], [[Snoop Dogg]], [[Wu-Tang Clan]], [[Bone Thugs-n-Harmony]], and [[Onyx (hip hop group)|Onyx]].<ref name=\"pharrell\"/> He also cites albums by Canadian R&B singer [[The Weeknd]] and Puerto Rican reggae band [[Cultura Prof\u00e9tica]] as his \"desert island albums.\"<ref name=10things>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/events/latin-awards/6546022/j-balvin-10-things-you-didnt-know-billboard-en-vivo-interview|title=10 Things You Didn't Know About J Balvin|work=Billboard|publisher=Prometheus Global Media|date=April 30, 2015|accessdate=March 30, 2018|author=Billboard Staff}}</ref> Pop singer [[Camila Cabello]] has cited J Balvin as a musical influence.<ref name=cabellobill>{{cite web|url= https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/8093913/camila-cabello-new-york-times-interview-album-havana-tour-fifth-harmony|title=5 Things We Learned From Camila Cabello's 'New York Times' Interview|work=Billboard|last=Braca|first=Nina|date=January 11, 2018|accessdate=March 30, 2018|publisher=Prometheus Global Media}}</ref>\n\n===Public image and lyrics===\nHis public image was described by Bishop by saying, \"J Balvin\u2019s not a bad boy, he\u2019s a good guy with a well-tended naughty side.\"<ref name=fader/> He often interacts with fans on social media sites such as [[Snapchat]] and [[Instagram]], and cites these platforms as essential for his success.<ref name=fader/> His musical partner Mazo explained, \u201cWe wanted to make music that was clean enough for your grandma to like, but sensual enough that the streets would like it too.\"<ref name=fader/> His lyrics have been described as more vulnerable than typical reggaeton lyrics, discussing interpersonal relationships, exemplified by the single \"Ay Vamos\". For this reason, he has been compared to Canadian artist [[Drake (rapper)|Drake]], a comparison with which J Balvin agrees.<ref name=\"mission\"/>\n\nOn the issue of [[misogyny]] in reggaeton, J Balvin notes, \"[I] have mothers, sisters, relatives. Part of what we did is change that misconception that reggaet\u00f3n is machista and misogynist. On the contrary, women are our biggest fans, and they inspire us.\"<ref name=Nickyandbalvin>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/latin/7767650/j-balvin-nicky-jam-reggaeton-cover-story|title=Reggaeton Superstars J Balvin and Nicky Jam on Conquering the Globe In the Trump Era|last=Cobo|first=Leila|date=April 20, 2017|accessdate=April 27, 2018|work=Billboard|publisher=Prometheus Global Media}}</ref>  He also refrains from singing about his country's [[history of Colombia|violent past]], saying that doing that exacerbates stereotypes about Colombians and that the country has made vast improvements since the days of [[Pablo Escobar]].<ref name=hotagain/> Instead, he discusses everyday life in his songs.<ref name=hotagain/> Luis Estrada of Universal Music Latino and Capitol Latin says of Balvin, \u201cHe breaks every rule of what people think reggaeton is, and they love him for that...He doesn\u2019t take himself too seriously.\u201d<ref name=hotagain/> J Balvin is unique also in that his dance crew on his videos and concerts are all male.<ref>{{Cite magazine|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-latin/j-balvins-latin-pop-crusade-201922/|title=J Balvin's Latin Pop Crusade|first=Suzy|last=Exposito|magazine=[[Rolling Stone]]|date=May 7, 2018}}</ref>\n\nDespite being fluent in English and frequently collaborating with English-speaking artists, J Balvin plans to only sing in Spanish. His goal is to make reggaeton a globally popular genre without having to sing in English to attain crossover success.<ref name=\"mission\"/> He explains, \"I want to keep making history in Spanish. I want to invite the mainstream into my world, and to my sound, and to what I\u2019m doing. And I want mainstream artists to respect me, and accept Latino artists as equals, without us having to sing in English. I want them to know that I can compete globally with whomever, in Spanish.\"<ref name=fader/> American artist [[Pharrell]] instead sings the hook in Spanish on \"Safari\", and J Balvin described having more American musicians singing in Spanish as one of his \"biggest dreams\".<ref name=nirvana/> However, he recorded his first all-English song with Pitbull and Camila Cabello for the 2017 soundtrack to ''[[The Fate of the Furious]]'', and explained that he is open to the idea of singing in English if the opportunity presents itself.<ref name=nirvana/>\n\n===Fashion===\n[[File:J Balvin - 6 AM - Festival de Vi\u00f1a del Mar 2017 (1).jpg|thumb|J Balvin is noted for his eccentric style, often wearing bright colors and dyeing his hair.]]\nJ Balvin has called fashion \u201chis life\u2019s passion, on the same level as music.\u201d<ref name=fader/> He appeared as an ambassador during the 2017 [[New York Fashion Week]], and has called for greater representation of Latinos in the fashion world.<ref name=nirvana/> The musician also appeared in [[Ovadia and Sons]]' Spring 2017 catalogue.<ref name=Nickyandbalvin/> He utilizes eccentric accessories such as cowboy hats, colorful tracksuits, and ripped jeans.<ref name=hotagain/> Isabela Raygoza described his aesthetic at the 2017 Latin Grammys as a \"Latin raver Eminem\" due to his neon blonde hair and brightly colored athletic clothing.<ref name=bestjbalvin/> His style often combines streetwear traditionally associated with reggaeton artists and classic luxury brands.<ref name=Nickyandbalvin/> J Balvin is influenced by musicians such as [[Kanye West]] and [[Pharrell Williams]] who have made forays into fashion. Discussing Pharrell's influence, J Balvin explained, \"I don't dress exactly like him, but I want to be like him in the cultural way. He opens the doors for a lot of new fashion designers and creates his own style. It's all about love with him and he's the culture.\"<ref name=\"pharrell\"/>\n\nIn January 2019 Balvin launched his exclusive Guess x J Balvin clothing collection. All the items were designed in Los Angeles and capture his playful, colorful and creative style.\n\n==Personal life==\nJ Balvin has spoken out about the [[Crisis in Venezuela (2012\u2013present)|Venezuelan economical crisis]] and the situation occurring at the country's border with Colombia, where thousands of Colombians have been forcibly deported.<ref name=protest>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/latin/6678447/j-balvin-protests-colombia-venezuela-border-crisis|title=J Balvin Raises Rallying Cry for Colombia-Venezuela Border Crisis|work=Billboard|publisher=Prometheus Global Media|date=August 28, 2015|accessdate=March 30, 2018}}</ref> He called the situation \"deplorable\" and created the social media campaign #LatinosSomosFamilia (We Latinos are Family), encouraging fans to sign a petition to support the displaced victims. The petition was soon signed by other prominent Latin artists including Colombian singer [[Maluma (singer)|Maluma]].<ref name=protest/> J Balvin's campaign was launched shortly after cancelling his performance on Miss USA 2015 in protest of Donald Trump.<ref name=protest/> He supports [[LGBT]] rights, explaining \"It\u2019s all about love. A lot of my closest friends are gay\", and dyed his hair rainbow colors to show support for [[Pride parade|Pride]] 2019.<ref name=throughhell>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2019/jul/27/j-balvin-on-breakdowns-escobar-and-beyonce-reggaeton|title=\u2018I\u2019ve been through hell\u2019: J Balvin on breakdowns, Escobar and Beyonc\u00e9|work=The Guardian|date=July 27, 2019|accessdate=March 24, 2020|last=Collins|first=Hattie}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2016, the singer was involved in a plane crash while leaving the Bahamas.<ref name=scary>{{cite news|url=http://www.foxnews.com/entertainment/2016/08/29/scary-j-balvin-survives-plane-crash-in-bahamas-calls-it-miracle.html|title=J Balvin survives plane crash in Bahamas, calls it 'a miracle'|work=Fox News|publisher=Fox Entertainment Group|date=August 29, 2016|accessdate=March 30, 2018}}</ref><ref name=survives>{{cite news|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/latin/7487846/j-balvin-survives-airplane-crash-scare-bahamas|title=J Balvin Survives Airplane Crash Scare, Rep Confirms|work=Billboard|publisher=Prometheus Global Media|date=August 26, 2016|accessdate=March 30, 2018}}</ref> While returning from a vacation with his family, the plane failed to take off properly and crash landed shortly after departing from the runway.<ref name=accidente>{{cite news|url=http://cnnespanol.cnn.com/2016/08/26/j-balvin-sufre-accidente-aereo-en-una-avioneta-en-bahamas/|title=J Balvin sufre accidente a\u00e9reo en una avioneta en Bahamas|work=CNN en Espa\u00f1ol|date=August 26, 2016|accessdate=March 30, 2018|publisher=CNN Corporation}}</ref> He posted a photo on Instagram of the small private plane after having landed in the bushes. Nobody was injured in the accident, and J Balvin called it \"a miracle.\"<ref name=scary/>\n\nJ Balvin experiences [[panic attacks]] and states that \"meditation saved [his] life\".<ref name=throughhell/> When his anxiety was at its worst, he recalled that \u201cI forgot about my happiness. I forgot about Jos\u00e9 (J Balvin's given name).\u201d<ref name=reasonstolove>{{cite web|url=http://people.com/chica/5-reasons-to-love-mi-gente-singer-j-balvin/|title=5 Reasons to Love 'Mi Gente' Singer J Balvin|work=People|last=Hansen|first=Lena|date=October 27, 2017|accessdate=March 30, 2018}}</ref> He is known for his tattoos and got his first tattoo when he was twelve years old.<ref name=gqtattoo>{{cite web|url=http://video.gq.com/watch/j-balvin-got-his-first-tattoo-when-he-was-12|title=Tattoo Tour - J Balvin|work=GQ|publisher=Cond\u00e9 Nast|date=March 20, 2018|accessdate=March 30, 2018}}</ref> His mother suffers from the rare genetic condition [[acute intermittent porphyria]], which causes seizures, chronic pain, and mental health difficulties. He has the word \"Familia\" tattooed on his chest in her honor.<ref name=reasonstolove/>\n\nUnlike many popular reggaeton singers who move to the United States upon gaining popularity, J Balvin continues to live in his hometown of Medellin, explaining, \"It keeps me real. I'm gonna be real everywhere I go, but I'm with my people, I'm connected to my roots \u2013 I'm in my country! I don't need to live somewhere else. I respect the ones who make it and leave their home base, but I'm good in Colombia.\".<ref name=nirvana/>\n\n== Discography ==\n{{Main|J Balvin discography}}\n* ''[[Real (album de J Balvin)|Real]]'' (2009)\n* ''[[La Familia (album)|La Familia]]'' (2013)\n* ''[[Energia (album)|Energ\u00eda]]'' (2016)\n* ''[[Vibras (album)|Vibras]]'' (2018)\n* ''[[Oasis (J Balvin and Bad Bunny album)|Oasis]]'' {{small|(with [[Bad Bunny]])}} (2019)\n* ''[[Colores]]'' (2020)\n\n==Tours==\n===Headlining===\n*La Familia Tour with [[Becky G]] (2015)\n*[[Energia (album)#Energia Tour|Energ\u00eda Tour]] (2016\u20132018)\n*[[Vibras Tour]] (2018)\n*[[Arcoiris Tour]] (2019)\n\n===Supporting===\n*[[The Sun Comes Out World Tour]] (2011)\n*[[Sex and Love Tour]] (2014)\n\n==Awards and nominations==\n{{Main|List of awards and nominations received by J Balvin}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|J Balvin}}\n*{{Official website|http://jbalvin.com/}}\n\n{{Portal bar|Biography|Colombia|Latin music}}\n{{J Balvin}}\n{{Lo Nuestro Award for Artist of the Year |state=collapsed}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Balvin, J.}}\n[[Category:1985 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Capitol Latin artists]]\n[[Category:Colombian artists]]\n[[Category:Colombian hip hop musicians]]\n[[Category:Colombian male singers]]\n[[Category:Colombian reggaeton artists]]\n[[Category:Latin Grammy Award winners]]\n[[Category:Latin music songwriters]]\n[[Category:Latin pop musicians]]\n[[Category:MTV EMA winners]]\n[[Category:People from Medell\u00edn]]\n[[Category:Universal Music Latin Entertainment artists]]\n[[Category:Urbano musicians]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2020}}\n{{short description|Colombian reggaeton singer}}\n{{Spanish name|Osorio|Balv\u00edn}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name             = J Balvin\n| image            = J Balvin - Ay Vamos - Festival de Vi\u00f1a del Mar 2017 (4).jpg\n| caption          = J Balvin performing in 2017\n| background       = solo_singer<!--INCLUDES rap artists-->\n| birth_name       = Jos\u00e9 \u00c1lvaro Osorio Balv\u00edn\n| birth_date       = {{birth date and age|mf=yes|1985|5|7}}\n| birth_place      = [[Medell\u00edn]], Colombia\n| genre            = {{hlist|[[Reggaeton]]|[[Latin pop]]|[[Urbano music|urbano]]|[[Hip hop music|hip hop]]}}\n| occupation       = Singer\n| instrument       = {{flatlist|\n* Vocals\n* guitar\n}}\n| years_active     = 2004\u2013present\n| label            = {{hlist|[[Capitol Latin]]|[[Universal Music Group|Universal]]|Infinity}}\n| associated_acts  = {{hlist|[[Bad Bunny]]|[[Ozuna (singer)|Ozuna]]|[[Anitta (singer)|Anitta]]}}\n| website          = {{URL|jbalvin.com}}\n}}\n'''Jos\u00e9 \u00c1lvaro Osorio Balv\u00edn''' (born May 7, 1985) is a Colombian [[reggaeton]] singer. Balvin was born in [[Medell\u00edn]], Colombia.<ref>[http://www.cromos.com.co/personajes/actualidad/articulo-143587-j-balvin-el-trono-del-reggaeton J. Balvin \u00a1100 % Reggueton!] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160404200633/http://www.cromos.com.co/personajes/actualidad/articulo-143587-j-balvin-el-trono-del-reggaeton |date=April 4, 2016 }} Viernes 9 de marzo de 2012</ref> At age 17, he moved to the United States. He moved to [[Oklahoma]] and [[New York (state)|New York]] to learn English. He then returned to Medell\u00edn and gained popularity performing at clubs in the city. He [[List of awards and nominations received by J Balvin|has won]] five [[Billboard Latin Music Awards]], four [[Latin Grammy Awards]], two [[MTV Video Music Awards]] and four [[Latin American Music Awards]] and received two [[Grammy Award]] nominations. In 2017 the [[BMI Awards|BMI Latin Awards]] named him the Contemporary Latin Songwriter of the Year for his contribution in latin music industry.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/latin/8256056/bmi-latin-awards-winners|title=BMI Latin Awards Honor Luis Fonsi, Residente, Horacio Palencia, J Balvin & Sony ATV|website=Billboard|access-date=November 20, 2019}}</ref> He became the first Latino artist to be a [[Lollapalooza]] headliner.\n\nHis breakthrough came in 2014 with the single \"[[6 AM]]\" featuring Puerto Rican singer [[Farruko]] which peaked at number 2 on the ''Billboard'' Hot Latin Songs chart. In 2016, he released ''[[Energia (album)|Energia]]'', which included the hit singles \"[[Ginza (song)|Ginza]]\", \"[[Bobo (J Balvin song)|Bobo]]\", \"[[Safari (J Balvin song)|Safari]]\", and \"Sigo Extra\u00f1\u00e1ndote\". In June 2017, J Balvin released the single \"[[Mi Gente (J Balvin and Willy William song)|Mi Gente]]\" with [[Willy William]]. On August 1, 2017, \"Mi Gente\" topped the Global Top 50 on [[Spotify]], and later reached one billion views on [[YouTube]]. In January 2018, he released the hit single \"[[Machika]]\" featuring Jeon and [[Anitta (singer)|Anitta]]. He collaborated with [[Cardi B]] and [[Bad Bunny]] on the US [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] number-one single \"[[I Like It (Cardi B, Bad Bunny and J Balvin song)|I Like It]]\", which was also nominated for the [[Grammy Award for Record of the Year]].\n\nThough his music is primarily reggaeton, J Balvin has experimented with a variety of musical genres in his work, including electronica, house music, trap, and R&B. His original musical inspirations included rock groups such as [[Metallica]] and [[Nirvana (band)|Nirvana]], and reggaeton artist [[Daddy Yankee]]. He has collaborated with [[Latin Americans|Latin American]] artists such as [[Ozuna (singer)|Ozuna]], [[Anitta (singer)|Anitta]], [[Nicky Jam]], [[Alejandro Sanz]], and [[Pitbull (rapper)|Pitbull]]. Despite working with many English-speaking artists such as  [[Beyonc\u00e9]], [[Pharrell Williams]], [[The Black Eyed Peas]], [[Cardi B]] and [[Major Lazer]], J Balvin continues to sing almost exclusively in Spanish, and hopes to introduce Spanish-language music to a global audience. He is also noted for his eclectic and colorful fashion sense.\n\n==Life and career==\n\n=== 1985\u20132013: Early life and career beginnings ===\nJ Balvin was born into a middle-class family in Medell\u00edn, Colombia on May 7, 1985.<ref name=\"mission\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/07/06/arts/music/j-balvin-energia-interview.html|title=J Balvin Is a Man With a Mission: Making Reggaeton Global|last=Coscarelli|first=Joe|date=July 5, 2016|work=New York Times|accessdate=March 30, 2018}}</ref> His father was an economist and business owner, and he grew up in a large home in the hills outside the city.<ref name=fader>{{cite web|url=http://www.thefader.com/2016/02/09/j-balvin-cover-story-interview|title=For J Balvin, Dignity is Not Negotiable|last=Bishop|first=Marlon|date=February 6, 2017|accessdate=March 30, 2018|work=[[The Fader]]|publisher=Andy Cohn}}</ref> He grew up listening to [[rock music|rock]] groups such as [[Metallica]] and [[Nirvana (band)|Nirvana]], and states that he incorporates the [[grunge]] aesthetic into his personal style, having a Nirvana tattoo on his knee.<ref name=nirvana>{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/features/reggaeton-star-j-balvin-on-nirvana-pharrell-guinness-honor-w471873|title=Reggaeton Ambassador J Balvin Talks Nirvana, Pharrell, Guinness Record|work=Rolling Stone|date=March 16, 2017|accessdate=March 30, 2018}}</ref> He developed an interest in reggaeton after listening to [[Daddy Yankee]]. He recalls that \u201cI was such a fan that I was copying his style, the way he moved onstage, his flows, his raps,\" comparing him to the reggaeton equivalent of [[Jay-Z]].<ref name=\"mission\"/> His father's business went bankrupt, and the family lost their home and car, requiring the family to move to a poorer neighborhood. On this period of his life, J Balvin notes, \u201cWhen I would go to the barrio, people saw me as a rich person, but when I\u2019m around rich people they see me as someone from the ghetto. It\u2019s all perceptions. I like moving between worlds. I feel equally comfortable in both.\u201d<ref name=fader/>\n\nWhen J Balvin was 16, he participated in an English-exchange program in [[Oklahoma]], but was disappointed by the experience, saying, \u201cI was expecting the U.S. that everyone knows from [[Hollywood]].\"<ref name=\"mission\"/> Soon after the program, he moved to [[New York City]] to further study English and music, living with an aunt on [[Staten Island]] and working as a dog walker.<ref name=fader/> During his time in New York, he became fascinated by the business savvy of New York rappers [[50 Cent]] and [[P. Diddy]].<ref name=\"mission\"/> J Balvin worked various jobs in New York, Miami, and Medell\u00edn, including working illegally in the United States as a roofer and house painter.<ref name=\"mission\"/> He ultimately decided to return to Colombia and began performing at various urban clubs in Medell\u00edn and increasing his social media following. He enrolled at the prestigious [[EAFIT University]] in Medell\u00edn for seven semesters, studying international business.<ref name=agridulce>{{cite web|url=https://www.elespectador.com/noticias/investigacion/el-grammy-agridulce-de-j-balvin-articulo-600614|title=El Grammy agridulce de J Balvin|work=El Espectador|last=Quevedo Hern\u00e1ndez|first=Norbey|date=November 21, 2015|accessdate=March 30, 2015|language=es}}</ref> At age 19, he began to seriously pursue a career in music and adopted the stage name J Balvin \u201cEl Negocio\", meaning \"The Business\" in English.<ref name=fader/>\n\nHe met his DJ and business partner David Rivera Mazo in a freestyle battle on the street in Medell\u00edn.<ref name=fader/> The two became fast friends and started producing and promoting their own music without a record label. J Balvin's early songs were described as \"basically poor imitations of commercial reggaeton from Puerto Rico,\" but he soon adopted a more relaxed, minimalist style in his music.<ref name=fader/> He signed to EMI Colombia in 2009 and soon after released the single \"Ella Me Cautiv\u00f3,\" which charted at number 35 on the ''Billboard'' [[Tropical Songs]] chart.<ref name=allmusicbio>{{cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/artist/j-balvin-mn0002385504/biography|title=J Balvin - Allmusic Biography|last=Jurek|first=Thom|accessdate=March 30, 2018}}</ref> He released his debut album, ''Real'', in 2009.<ref name=\"pharrell\">{{cite web|url=http://www.xxlmag.com/news/2017/02/j-balvin-interview-pharrell/|title=J BALVIN\u2019S HIP-HOP CONNECTION INCLUDES LIFE ADVICE FROM PHARRELL|work=[[XXL (magazine)|XXL]]|publisher=Townsquare Media|last=Krastz|first=Roger|date=February 10, 2017}}</ref> In 2012, J Balvin released a mixtape featuring many of his early hits in Colombia, including \"En Lo Oscuro\" and \"Como un Animal.\" His first international hit was the one-night-stand-themed \"Yo Te Lo Dije\", and signed with Universal subsidiary Capitol Latin a year later.<ref name=fader/>\n\n=== 2014\u201316: \"6AM\" success and ''La Familia'' ===\n[[File:Lesin valencia junto j balvin (cropped).JPG|thumb|left|J Balvin in June 2014]]\nIn February 2014, J Balvin released a new track entitled \"[[6 AM]],\" featuring Puerto Rican singer [[Farruko]]. J Balvin described the lyrical content of the song as the \"Latin version of ''[[The Hangover]]'',\" where the two singers attempt to remember what happened during a night of partying.<ref name=farruko6am>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/events/year-in-music-2014/6405612/j-balvin-farruko-on-6-am-number-one-charts-2014|title=J Balvin on His No. 1 Hit '6 AM' Being the 'Latin Version' of 'The Hangover'|work=Billboard|publisher=Prometheus Global Media|date=December 12, 2014|accessdate=March 30, 2018}}</ref> The song debuted at number 43 on the ''Billboard'' Latin Airplay chart in February and reached number one in May.<ref name=farruko6am/> His album ''La Familia'' reached number ten on the ''Billboard'' Top Latin Albums chart, spending 122 weeks on the chart in total.<ref name=lafamiliachart>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/music/j-balvin/chart-history/latin-albums/song/803617|title=J Balvin - La Familia Chart History|work=Billboard|publisher=Prometheus Global Media|accessdate=May 15, 2018}}</ref>\n\nShortly after, J Balvin released his second track in the United States, \"[[Ay Vamos]],\" which solidified his mark in the Latin urban market.<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web|url=http://latino.foxnews.com/latino/entertainment/2015/06/25/colombian-singer-j-balvin-cancels-miss-usa-appearance-over-donald-trumps-mexico/|title=Colombian singer cancels Miss USA appearance over Donald Trump\u2019s comments|work=[[Fox News Latino]]|accessdate=June 25, 2015}}</ref> It won a Latin Grammy Award for Best Urban Song.<ref name=allmusicbio/> This was a bonus track on the deluxe edition of J Balvin's album ''La Familia B-Sides'' The music video is one of the most watched Latin music videos of all time, at over one billion views. The song went to number one on the ''Billboard'' Hot Latin Songs chart in 2015. The remix, featuring Nicky Jam and [[French Montana]] was used in the soundtrack to the film ''[[Furious 7]]''. J Balvin performed the track at the 2015 Premios Lo Nuestro and the ''Billboard'' Latin Music Awards. J  Balvin has been featured on remixes of \"Sorry\" by [[Justin Bieber]], \"The Way\" and \"Problem\" by [[Ariana Grande]], \"Blurred Lines\" by [[Robin Thicke]], \"Maps\" by [[Maroon 5]], and \"Stuck on a Feeling\" by [[Prince Royce]].<ref name=\"auto\"/> J Balvin was the first Colombian singer to record with \"The Prince of Bachata\" and establishing itself as an international artist.<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\nJ Balvin swept the urban category at the 2015 [[Premios Lo Nuestro]], including \"Urban Artist of the Year,\" \"Urban Album of the Year,\" \"Urban Song of the Year\" and \"Urban Collaboration of the Year.\" On February 12, the nominees for the [[Billboard Latin Music Awards|''Billboard'' Latin Music Awards]] were announced, and J Balvin was nominated 13 times, of these nominations, eight were in the same category twice \"Ay Vamos\" and \"6 AM,\" being the most nominated Colombian and the first urban artist from Colombia. J Balvin won New Artist, Latin Rhythm Song of the Year, and Latin Rhythm Song Artist of the Year, where he dedicated the award to his home country of Colombia.<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n[[File:J Balvin 2015.jpg|thumb|Balvin performing in 2015]]\nIn June 2015, it was announced that J Balvin had cancelled his performance on [[Miss USA 2015]] to protest [[Donald Trump]]'s inflammatory comments insulting illegal immigrants,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/latin/6605876/j-balvin-cancels-miss-usa-performance-donald-trump-latin-comments|title=J Balvin Cancels Miss USA Performance After Donald Trump's Comments on illegal immigrants: Exclusive|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|accessdate=June 25, 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"auto\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.people.com/article/j-balvin-cancels-miss-usa-performance-donald-trumps-comments-mexicans|title=J Balvin Cancels Miss USA Performance After Donald Trump Comments About Illegal Immigrants : People.com|work=[[People (magazine)|People]]|accessdate=June 25, 2015}}</ref> saying, \"During [Trump's] [[Donald Trump presidential campaign, 2016|presidential campaign kickoff speech last week]] [June 2015], Trump accused illegal immigrants of bringing drugs, crime and rapists to the U.S.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.latintimes.com/miss-usa-2015-show-j-balvin-cancels-appearance-following-donald-trumps-comments-324822|title=Miss USA 2015 Show: J Balvin Cancels Appearance Following Donald Trump's Comments On Latinos|author=Armando Tinoco|date=June 25, 2015|work=[[Latin Times]]|accessdate=June 25, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wafb.com/story/29402543/j-balvin-cancels-miss-usa-appearance-over-trumps-comments|title=J Balvin cancels Miss USA appearance over Trump's comments|date=June 24, 2015|work=[[Associated Press]] via [[WAFB]]|accessdate=June 25, 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150626144333/http://www.wafb.com/story/29402543/j-balvin-cancels-miss-usa-appearance-over-trumps-comments|archivedate=June 26, 2015}}</ref> His live performance had been scheduled for July 12, 2015 in [[Louisiana]], which would have been J Balvin's first performance on national mainstream television.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/latin/6605876/j-balvin-cancels-miss-usa-performance-donald-trump-latin-comments|title=J Balvin Cancels Miss USA Performance After Donald Trump's Comments on Latins: Exclusive|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|accessdate=June 25, 2015}}</ref>\n\n=== 2016\u201317: ''Energia'' ===\nOn January 16, 2016, J Balvin premiered his new single \"Ginza\" from his upcoming album, at the Premios Juventud. Later that week, he premiered the music video on Vevo. The music video broke the record for the most views for a Latin music video in the first 24 hours, at over two million views. Since then, the video has racked up over 807 million views.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=zZjSX01P5dE|title=YouTube Ginza video count|last=|first=|date=|website=|publisher=[[YouTube]]|access-date=}}</ref> The song reached number one on ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]''{{'}}s [[Hot Latin Songs]] chart for the week of October 17, 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/charts/latin-songs|title=Latin Music: Top Latin Songs|website=Billboard.com}}</ref> The song also set a new [[Guinness World Record]] for the longest stay at number one on the chart.<ref name=nirvana/> J Balvin became the first artist to receive a [[RIAA certification|diamond]] certification in the Latin field from the RIAA, denoting digital sales of 600,000 units for his songs \"6 AM\" and \"Ay Vamos.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=J Balvin Earns First-Ever RIAA Latin Digital Diamond Honor|url=https://www.riaa.com/newsitem.php?content_selector=riaa-news-gold-and-platinum&news_month_filter=10&news_year_filter=2015&id=6BC000B7-6D8B-5E62-7931-D65D5736F813|publisher=RIAA|accessdate=October 27, 2015|date=October 26, 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151027214158/http://www.riaa.com/newsitem.php?content_selector=riaa-news-gold-and-platinum&news_month_filter=10&news_year_filter=2015&id=6BC000B7-6D8B-5E62-7931-D65D5736F813|archivedate=October 27, 2015}}</ref> Andrew Casillas of ''Rolling Stone'' wrote that \"with its deliciously liquid beat, [\"Ginza\"] among the finest three minutes in reggaet\u00f3n history.\"<ref name=Energiarollingstone>{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/lists/10-best-latin-albums-of-2016-w458207/j-balvin-energia-w458211|title=J Balvin - ''Energia'': 10 Best Latin Albums of 2016|last=Casillas|first=Andrew|date=December 30, 2016|accessdate=March 30, 2018|work=Rolling Stone}}</ref>\n\nOn June 24, 2016, J Balvin released his fourth studio album ''[[Energia (album)|Energia]]''. ''Energia'' debuted at number one on the ''Billboard'' Top Latin Albums chart, signifying his first time topping that chart.<ref name=energiabow>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/biz/articles/7430971/j-balvins-energia-bows-at-no-1-on-top-latin-albums|title=J Balvin's 'Energia' Bows at No. 1 on Top Latin Albums|work=Billboard|last=Mendizabal|first=Amaya|date=July 7, 2016|accessdate=April 27, 2018}}</ref> It had the third-best debut sales of any Latin artist in 2016, after [[Juan Gabriel]]'s ''Los Duo 2'' and [[Banda MS|Banda Sinaloense MS de Sergio Lizarraga]]'s ''Que Bendicion''. It also debuted at number 38 on the all-genre ''Billboard'' 200.<ref name=energiabow/> The album featured collaborations with Daddy Yankee, [[Juanes]], [[Pharrell]], and [[Yandel]].<ref name=didntknowenergia>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/latin/7415687/j-balvins-new-album-energia|title=7 Things You Didn't Know About J Balvin's New Album 'Energia'|work=Billboard|last=Fernandez|first=Suzette|date=June 23, 2016|accessdate=April 27, 2018}}</ref> He launched 3 hit singles from the album, \"Bobo,\" \"Safari,\" and \"Sigo Extranandote,\" which all reached the top 10 of the Latin charts.  \"Bobo\" spent a week at the top of the ''Billboard'' Hot Latin Songs chart.<ref name=energiabow/> Mario Prunes of Allmusic described ''Energia'' as \"an album that knew it was going to be an international blockbuster almost a year before its release,\" due to the success of \"Ginza\".<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.allmusic.com/album/energia-mw0002952969|title= Review: J Balvin - Energia|work= Allmusic|accessdate=April 19, 2018|last=Prunes|first=Mario}}</ref> ''Rolling Stone'' ranked the album number four on the magazine's list of the 10 Best Latin Albums of 2016.<ref name=Energiarollingstone/>\n\n[[File:J Balvin - Sigo Extra\u00f1\u00e1ndote - Festival de Vi\u00f1a del Mar 2017 (2).jpg|thumb|J Balvin performing \"Sigo Extra\u00f1\u00e1ndote\" in Chile in March 2017|alt=|left]]\n\nIn promotion of the album, J Balvin embarked on the ''Energia'' Tour, traveling with several special guests including [[French Montana]], [[Zion & Lennox]], [[Bad Bunny]], and [[Steve Aoki]], the latter of which appeared as a surprise for fans during the last stop of the tour in [[Miami]].<ref name=energiaaoki>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/latin/7998695/j-balvin-energia-tour-finale|title=J Balvin Brings Out Steve Aoki for Energia Tour Finale in Miami|work=Billboard|last=Fernandez|first=Suzette|date=October 14, 2017|accessdate=April 27, 2018}}</ref> That same year, J Balvin featured on \"Cuando Seas Grande\" by Spanish musician [[Alejandro Sanz]] and American singer [[Sofia Carson]]\u00b4s \"Love is the Name.\"<ref name=allmusicbio/> He launched a partnership with SoundCloud and Buchanan's Whiskey in a project called Es Nuestro Momento, where fans can access J Balvin's previously unreleased a capella vocals and create personalized remixes of his songs.<ref name=forbes>{{cite web|url= https://www.forbes.com/sites/hughmcintyre/2017/03/13/j-balvin-explains-why-his-spanish-language-music-does-so-well-in-america/#1bdc711160a5|title=J. Balvin Explains Why His Spanish-Language Music Does So Well In America|work=Forbes|publisher=Forbes Media, LLC.|last=McIntyre|first=Hugh|date=March 13, 2017|accessdate=March 30, 2018}}</ref> Buchanan's Whisky also served as a sponsor for the ''Energia'' Tour in honor of Hispanic Heritage Month.<ref name=energiaaoki/>\n\n=== 2017\u20132018: International success: \"Mi Gente\" & ''Vibras'' ===\nOn June 30, 2017, J Balvin released his new single along with the official music video \"[[Mi Gente (J Balvin and Willy William song)|Mi Gente]]\" featuring [[Willy William]]. On August 1, 2017, \"Mi Gente\" became the number 1 song in the world according to Global Top 50 on [[Spotify]]. It soon reached 1 billion views on [[YouTube]]. In September 2017, the song was remixed with American artist [[Beyonc\u00e9]].<ref name=livemoment>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/8023274/j-balvin-lives-his-moment-with-chart-and-touring-success|title=J Balvin Lives His Moment With Chart And Touring Success|last=Estevez|first=Marjua|date=November 8, 2017|accessdate=April 19, 2018|work=Billboard|publisher=Prometheus Global Media}}</ref> The remix reached #3 in the United States, giving Balvin his first USA top ten single. J Balvin and Willy William released six more \"Mi Gente\" remixes with [[Steve Aoki]], [[Alesso]], [[Cedric Gervais]], [[Dillon Francis]], [[Sunnery James & Ryan Marciano]], and Henry Fong.<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/latin/8006819/j-balvin-mi-gente-remixes-steve-aoki-cedric-gervais-dillon-francis|title= J Balvin Drops Six New 'Mi Gente' Remixes With Steve Aoki, Cedric Gervais, Dillon Francis & More|work= billboard.com|accessdate=October 25, 2017}}</ref> Despite the song's success, \"Mi Gente\" did not win any awards at the 2017 Latin Grammy Awards, with many awards going to [[Luis Fonsi]]'s hit \"[[Despacito]]\".<ref name=bestjbalvin>{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/pictures/latin-grammys-2017-luis-fonsi-residente-win-big-w512064/best-j-balvin-brings-global-starpower-to-the-stage-w512092|title=J Balvin brings global starpower to the stage|last=Raygoza|first=Isabela|date=November 17, 2017|accessdate=March 30, 2018|work=Rolling Stone}}</ref> At the ceremony, he performed \"Mi Gente\" as well as \"Si Tu Novio Te Deja Sola\" alongside [[Bad Bunny]] and his remix of \"[[Unforgettable (French Montana song)|Unforgettable]]\" with [[French Montana]].<ref name=bestjbalvin/>\n\nOn January 19, 2018, J Balvin released his new single along with the official music video \"Machika\" featuring Jeon and [[Anitta]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Marjua|first1=Estevez|title=J Balvin, Anitta & Jeon Are War-Ready in 'Machika' Premiere: Watch|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/latin/8095054/j-balvin-anitta-jeon-machika-premiere|website=Billboard|publisher=Billboard|accessdate=January 19, 2018}}</ref> His collaboration with Nicky Jam, \"X,\" was released on March 1, 2018 and the music video received 288 million views on YouTube in less than a month.<ref name=xnyt>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/aponline/2018/03/26/arts/ap-us-music-nicky-jam.html|title=Nicky Jam's Friendship With J Balvin Produces a New Hit: 'X'|work=New York Times|date=March 26, 2018|accessdate=March 30, 2018|publisher=A.G. Sulzberger}}</ref> Nicky Jam stated that he attributes the success of \"X\" to J Balvin's contribution.<ref name=xnyt/> He also appeared on [[Cardi B]]\u00b4s ''[[Invasion of Privacy (album)|Invasion of Privacy]]'' album, with Bad Bunny on the song \"I Like It.\"<ref name=allmusicbio/> It became Balvin's first number one single on the US [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]].<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/8463605/cardi-b-i-like-it-hot-100-number-one-j-balvin-bad-bunny |title=Cardi B Becomes First Female Rapper With Two Billboard Hot 100 No. 1s, as 'I Like It,' With Bad Bunny & J Balvin, Follows 'Bodak Yellow' to the Top |last=Trust |first=Gary |date=July 2, 2018 |work=Billboard |accessdate=July 2, 2018}}</ref>\n\nJ Balvin released the album ''[[Vibras]]'' on May 25, 2018.<ref name=vibrasinsta>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/latin/8299811/j-balvin-new-album-vibras|title=J Balvin Sets Release Date for New Album 'Vibras'|last=Fernandez|first=Suzette|date=April 9, 2018|accessdate=April 19, 2018|work=Billboard|publisher=Prometheus Global Media}}</ref> The two lead singles from the album were \u201cMachika\u201d and \u201cAhora.\u201d<ref name=vibrasinsta/> On April 23, 2018, J Balvin announced the dates for his Vibras tour revealing the 27 cities where he will be [[Performance|performing]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/j-balvin-plots-north-american-vibras-tour-w519448|title=J Balvin Plots North American 'Vibras' Tour|work=Rolling Stone|access-date=April 26, 2018}}</ref> ''Vibras'' claimed the record for the most-streamed Latin album in 24 hours on the streaming platform for 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/latin/8459722/j-balvin-vibras-apple-music-record|title=J Balvin's 'Vibras' Album Has Biggest First Week Ever for a Latin Artist on Apple Music|work=Billboard|last=Fernandez|first=Suzette|date=6 June 2018|accessdate=7 June 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180608201248/https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/latin/8459722/j-balvin-vibras-apple-music-record|archive-date=8 June 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> In the United States, it debuted at number one on the [[Top Latin Albums]] chart for the issue dated 9 June 2018. According to [[Nielsen SoundScan|Nielsen Music]], the record sold 22,000 [[album-equivalent units]] and became Balvin's second number-one album on the chart, following ''Energia'' in 2016. Additionally, ''Vibras'' scored the largest streaming week ever for a Latin album by an artist; its songs were streamed 16.1&nbsp;million times.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/8459608/j-balvin-vibras-no-1-top-latin-albums|title=J Balvin Lands Biggest Week of 2018 For a Latin Album With No. 1 Debut of 'Vibras'|work=Billboard|last=Bustios|first=Pamela|date=6 June 2018|accessdate=6 June 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180608085812/https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/8459608/j-balvin-vibras-no-1-top-latin-albums|archive-date=8 June 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> Subsequently, it debuted at number 15 on the US [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]] and became his highest-charting album on the chart.<ref name=\"200peak\"/> \n\nIn an interview with Ebro Darden for Beats 1 Radio on [[Apple Music]] in April 2018, Balvin described the sound of the record as 33% [[dancehall]], 33% [[Contemporary R&B|R&B]], and 33% reggaeton. Balvin further elaborated that a lot of love was put into the album's work and that contains different vibes, hence the name, ''Vibras'', \"The real meaning of this album was what's going on with Spanish music that's going so global, the fact that we did an album that the beats are so amazing that you don't have to understand what we say, you just have to love the songs.\"<ref name=\"complexinterview\">{{cite web|url=http://www.complex.com/music/2018/05/j-balvin-new-album-vibras-is-here|title=J Balvin's New Album 'Vibras' Is Here|work=[[Complex (magazine)|Complex]]|last=Pimentel|first=Julia|date=25 May 2018|accessdate=25 May 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180525213803/http://www.complex.com/music/2018/05/j-balvin-new-album-vibras-is-here|archive-date=25 May 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== 2019\u2013present: ''Oasis'' and ''Colores''===\n[[File:Bad Bunny 2019 by Glenn Francis.jpg|thumb|170px|J Balvin released the 2019 album ''Oasis'' in collaboration with Puerto Rican rapper [[Bad Bunny]] (pictured)]]\nOn June 27, 2019, J Balvin released his new album in collaboration with Bad Bunny titled ''[[Oasis (J Balvin and Bad Bunny album)|Oasis]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-latin/j-balvin-bad-bunny-oasis-joint-album-852950/|title=J Balvin, Bad Bunny Continue Can\u2019t-Miss Run With Joint Album \u2018Oasis\u2019|last=Leight|first=Elias|date=June 28, 2019|website=Rolling Stone|language=en-US|access-date=June 28, 2019}}</ref> The record was released overnight and was deemed a \"surprise\" release.<ref name=nytimesoasis>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/06/28/arts/music/bad-bunny-j-balvin-oasis.html|last=Coscarelli|first=Joe|title=How J Balvin and Bad Bunny Made Their Surprise Album, \u2018Oasis\u2019\n|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=June 28, 2019|accessdate=November 26, 2019}}</ref> The two artists first met at a J Balvin concert in Puerto Rico, when Bad Bunny was working on releasing music on SoundCloud, and then collaborated on the 2017 track \u201cSi Tu Novio Te Deja Sola\u201d. The chemistry between the two was so strong that they came up with the idea to release a joint album.<ref name=nytimesoasis/> ''Oasis'' peaked at number nine on the ''Billboard'' Hot 100<ref name=oasishot100>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/music/J-Balvin/chart-history/billboard-200|title=J Balvin Chart History|work=Billboard|publisher=Prometheus Global Media|accessdate=November 26, 2019}}</ref> and topped the ''Billboard'' US Latin Albums chart.<ref name=oasislatinalbums>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/music/J-Balvin/chart-history/latin-albums|title=J Balvin US Latin Albums Chart|work=Billboard|publisher=Prometheus Global Media|accessdate=November 26, 2019}}</ref> The album was nominated for Best Latin Rock, Urban or Alternative Album at the [[62nd Annual Grammy Awards|2020 Grammy Awards]] and was named one of ''Rolling Stone''\u2018s Best Latin Albums of 2019.<ref name=bloody>{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-latin/j-balvin-rojo-video-colores-track-list-957599/|title=J Balvin Gets Bloody in Haunting New \u2018Rojo\u2019 Video|last=Exposito|first=Suzy|work=Rolling Stone|date=February 27, 2020|accessdate=March 25, 2020}}</ref>\n\nHis collaboration with Spanish singer [[Rosal\u00eda (singer)|Rosal\u00eda]] \"[[Con altura]]\" won Best Urban Song at the [[20th Annual Latin Grammy Awards|2019 Latin Grammy Awards]].<ref name=blancoRS>{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/j-balvin-blanco-music-video-913121/|title= Watch J Balvin\u2019s Futuristic Music Video for \u2018Blanco\u2019\n|last=Zemler|first=Emily|date=November 15, 2019|accessdate=March 25, 2020|work=Rolling Stone}}</ref> The song received positive reviews from critics and ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' ranked it 5th on their list of 100 Best Songs of 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/list/8545893/best-songs-of-2019-top-100|title=The 100 Best Songs of 2019: Staff List|website=Billboard|access-date=2019-12-30}}</ref> J Balvin was a guest performer in the [[Super Bowl LIV halftime show]] headlined by [[Jennifer Lopez]] and [[Shakira]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Bajuder |first1=David |title=Jennifer Lopez, Shakira in joyful, exuberant Super Bowl LIV halftime show |url=https://www.denverpost.com/2020/02/02/jennifer-lopez-shakira-super-bowl-liv-halftime-show-review/ |publisher=The Denver Post |agency=The Associated Press |accessdate=3 February 2020 |date=3 February 2020}}</ref> He also collaborated with [[Major Lazer]] and Dominican dembow singer [[El Alfa]] on the single \"[[Que Calor]]\" in September 2019.<ref name=blancoRS/> \n\nIn November 2019, J Balvin released the music video for the single \"Blanco\", which introduced a \"futuristic, all-white environment filled with hypnotic dancers and flying cats\".<ref name=blancoRS/> On March 20, 2020, J Balvin released the album ''[[Colores]]'', in which every song is named after a color except the song \"Arco\u00edris\" (the Spanish word for rainbow).<ref name=coloresguardian>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2020/mar/22/j-balvin-colores-review-reggaeton-hooks-ideas|title=J Balvin: Colores review \u2013 a riot of hooks and ideas|work=The Guardian|last=Cragg|first=Michael|date=March 22, 2020|accessdate=March 24, 2020}}</ref><ref name=coloresguardian2>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2020/mar/19/j-balvin-colores-review|title=J Balvin: Colores review \u2013 with this much style, who needs substance?|work=The Guardian|last=Petridis|first=Alexis|date=March 19, 2020|accessdate=March 24, 2020}}</ref> The album contains influences from dancehall, R&B, and electronica, and features Nigerian [[afrobeats]] artist [[Mr Eazi]] on the song \"Arco\u00edris\".<ref name=coloresguardian/><ref name=coloresguardian2/> Suzy Exposito of ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' called the album \"sophisticated show of Balvin\u2019s sonic palette\".<ref name=RScolores>{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-album-reviews/j-balvin-colores-969836/|title=J Balvin Nuances His Cosmopolitan Reggaeton Sound on \u2018Colores\u2019|date=March 20, 2020|accessdate=March 24, 2020|work=Rolling Stone|publisher=Jann Wenner}}</ref> The album artwork was created by Japanese artist [[Takashi Murakami]].<ref name=coloresguardian2/> Balvin collaborated with Murakami for the music videos and album and single artwork, which notably feature Murakami's flowers, as well as American clothing brand [[Guess (clothing)|Guess]] on a [[capsule collection]] inspired by the album.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.highsnobiety.com/p/guess-j-balvin-spring-2020/|title=J Balvin's New GUESS Collection Is Inspired by His Upcoming Album|website=[[Highsnobiety]]|last=Sawyer|first=Jonathan|date=26 February 2020|accessdate=28 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Artistry==\n===Musical style===\nCritics have contrasted J Balvin's musical style from the first internationally popular wave of reggaeton led by Daddy Yankee. Marlon Bishop of ''The Fader'' described his vocal delivery as a \"gentle drawl\", differing greatly from the rapid-fire, aggressive delivery of earlier reggaeton acts.<ref name=fader/> He generally sings over his beats as opposed to rapping, and favors a more melodic, pop-influenced style.<ref name=hotagain>{{cite web|url=http://www.thefader.com/2015/11/23/j-balvin-reggaeton-interview|title=How J Balvin Made Reggaeton Hot Again|last=Bishop|first=Marlon|work=The Fader|date=November 23, 2015|accessdate=March 30, 2018}}</ref> Describing his music's production, Bishop writes, \"Instead of the hard-edged, maximalist beats of the first wave, Balvin\u2019s tracks are moody and spaced out\".<ref name=fader/>  He frequently works with Medellin-based writer/producers Alejandro \u201cSky\u201d Ramirez and Carlo Alejandro \u201cMosty\u201d Pati\u00f1o, whom he often name-drops in his songs.<ref name=medellinexports>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/magazine-feature/7693380/medellin-latin-stars-maluma-j-balvin|title=Medellin's Musical Exports: Maluma, J Balvin & More Stars the Colombian City Spawned|last=Cobo|first=Leila|date=February 16, 2017|work=Billboard|publisher=Prometheus Global Media}}</ref> He has been credited with popularizing a new style of reggaeton based in Medellin, along with [[Maluma (singer)|Maluma]] and Puerto Ricans who have relocated to the city to become involved in the reggaeton scene, such as Nicky Jam and Farruko.<ref name=hotagain/>\n\n{{multiple image\n| footer = In addition to the primary inspiration of Daddy Yankee, J Balvin has cited both salsa musician [[H\u00e9ctor Lavoe]] (''left'') and rapper [[Snoop Dogg]] (''right'') as influential for him and his music\n| image1 = El Cantante.jpg\n| width1 = 216\n| alt1 = H\u00e9ctor Lavoe in an undated photo\n| image2 = Snoop Dogg 2012.jpg\n| width2 = 146\n| alt2 = Snoop Dogg with a beanie in a white collared shirt\n| align = right}}\n\nThough he cites Daddy Yankee as his biggest musical inspiration, J Balvin's earliest influences were rock bands such as Metallica and Nirvana, as well as salsa legend [[Hector Lavoe]].<ref name=nirvana/> He has covered Nirvana's hit \"[[Smells Like Teen Spirit]]\" in live performances.<ref name=nirvana/> As a teenager, he listened to hip-hop artists such as [[2Pac]], [[The Notorious B.I.G.]], [[Snoop Dogg]], [[Wu-Tang Clan]], [[Bone Thugs-n-Harmony]], and [[Onyx (hip hop group)|Onyx]].<ref name=\"pharrell\"/> He also cites albums by Canadian R&B singer [[The Weeknd]] and Puerto Rican reggae band [[Cultura Prof\u00e9tica]] as his \"desert island albums.\"<ref name=10things>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/events/latin-awards/6546022/j-balvin-10-things-you-didnt-know-billboard-en-vivo-interview|title=10 Things You Didn't Know About J Balvin|work=Billboard|publisher=Prometheus Global Media|date=April 30, 2015|accessdate=March 30, 2018|author=Billboard Staff}}</ref> Pop singer [[Camila Cabello]] has cited J Balvin as a musical influence.<ref name=cabellobill>{{cite web|url= https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/8093913/camila-cabello-new-york-times-interview-album-havana-tour-fifth-harmony|title=5 Things We Learned From Camila Cabello's 'New York Times' Interview|work=Billboard|last=Braca|first=Nina|date=January 11, 2018|accessdate=March 30, 2018|publisher=Prometheus Global Media}}</ref>\n\n===Public image and lyrics===\nHis public image was described by Bishop by saying, \"J Balvin\u2019s not a bad boy, he\u2019s a good guy with a well-tended naughty side.\"<ref name=fader/> He often interacts with fans on social media sites such as [[Snapchat]] and [[Instagram]], and cites these platforms as essential for his success.<ref name=fader/> His musical partner Mazo explained, \u201cWe wanted to make music that was clean enough for your grandma to like, but sensual enough that the streets would like it too.\"<ref name=fader/> His lyrics have been described as more vulnerable than typical reggaeton lyrics, discussing interpersonal relationships, exemplified by the single \"Ay Vamos\". For this reason, he has been compared to Canadian artist [[Drake (rapper)|Drake]], a comparison with which J Balvin agrees.<ref name=\"mission\"/>\n\nOn the issue of [[misogyny]] in reggaeton, J Balvin notes, \"[I] have mothers, sisters, relatives. Part of what we did is change that misconception that reggaet\u00f3n is machista and misogynist. On the contrary, women are our biggest fans, and they inspire us.\"<ref name=Nickyandbalvin>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/latin/7767650/j-balvin-nicky-jam-reggaeton-cover-story|title=Reggaeton Superstars J Balvin and Nicky Jam on Conquering the Globe In the Trump Era|last=Cobo|first=Leila|date=April 20, 2017|accessdate=April 27, 2018|work=Billboard|publisher=Prometheus Global Media}}</ref>  He also refrains from singing about his country's [[history of Colombia|violent past]], saying that doing that exacerbates stereotypes about Colombians and that the country has made vast improvements since the days of [[Pablo Escobar]].<ref name=hotagain/> Instead, he discusses everyday life in his songs.<ref name=hotagain/> Luis Estrada of Universal Music Latino and Capitol Latin says of Balvin, \u201cHe breaks every rule of what people think reggaeton is, and they love him for that...He doesn\u2019t take himself too seriously.\u201d<ref name=hotagain/> J Balvin is unique also in that his dance crew on his videos and concerts are all male.<ref>{{Cite magazine|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-latin/j-balvins-latin-pop-crusade-201922/|title=J Balvin's Latin Pop Crusade|first=Suzy|last=Exposito|magazine=[[Rolling Stone]]|date=May 7, 2018}}</ref>\n\nDespite being fluent in English and frequently collaborating with English-speaking artists, J Balvin plans to only sing in Spanish. His goal is to make reggaeton a globally popular genre without having to sing in English to attain crossover success.<ref name=\"mission\"/> He explains, \"I want to keep making history in Spanish. I want to invite the mainstream into my world, and to my sound, and to what I\u2019m doing. And I want mainstream artists to respect me, and accept Latino artists as equals, without us having to sing in English. I want them to know that I can compete globally with whomever, in Spanish.\"<ref name=fader/> American artist [[Pharrell]] instead sings the hook in Spanish on \"Safari\", and J Balvin described having more American musicians singing in Spanish as one of his \"biggest dreams\".<ref name=nirvana/> However, he recorded his first all-English song with Pitbull and Camila Cabello for the 2017 soundtrack to ''[[The Fate of the Furious]]'', and explained that he is open to the idea of singing in English if the opportunity presents itself.<ref name=nirvana/>\n\n===Fashion===\n[[File:J Balvin - 6 AM - Festival de Vi\u00f1a del Mar 2017 (1).jpg|thumb|J Balvin is noted for his eccentric style, often wearing bright colors and dyeing his hair.]]\nJ Balvin has called fashion \u201chis life\u2019s passion, on the same level as music.\u201d<ref name=fader/> He appeared as an ambassador during the 2017 [[New York Fashion Week]], and has called for greater representation of Latinos in the fashion world.<ref name=nirvana/> The musician also appeared in [[Ovadia and Sons]]' Spring 2017 catalogue.<ref name=Nickyandbalvin/> He utilizes eccentric accessories such as cowboy hats, colorful tracksuits, and ripped jeans.<ref name=hotagain/> Isabela Raygoza described his aesthetic at the 2017 Latin Grammys as a \"Latin raver Eminem\" due to his neon blonde hair and brightly colored athletic clothing.<ref name=bestjbalvin/> His style often combines streetwear traditionally associated with reggaeton artists and classic luxury brands.<ref name=Nickyandbalvin/> J Balvin is influenced by musicians such as [[Kanye West]] and [[Pharrell Williams]] who have made forays into fashion. Discussing Pharrell's influence, J Balvin explained, \"I don't dress exactly like him, but I want to be like him in the cultural way. He opens the doors for a lot of new fashion designers and creates his own style. It's all about love with him and he's the culture.\"<ref name=\"pharrell\"/>\n\nIn January 2019 Balvin launched his exclusive Guess x J Balvin clothing collection. All the items were designed in Los Angeles and capture his playful, colorful and creative style.\n\n==Personal life==\nJ Balvin has spoken out about the [[Crisis in Venezuela (2012\u2013present)|Venezuelan economical crisis]] and the situation occurring at the country's border with Colombia, where thousands of Colombians have been forcibly deported.<ref name=protest>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/latin/6678447/j-balvin-protests-colombia-venezuela-border-crisis|title=J Balvin Raises Rallying Cry for Colombia-Venezuela Border Crisis|work=Billboard|publisher=Prometheus Global Media|date=August 28, 2015|accessdate=March 30, 2018}}</ref> He called the situation \"deplorable\" and created the social media campaign #LatinosSomosFamilia (We Latinos are Family), encouraging fans to sign a petition to support the displaced victims. The petition was soon signed by other prominent Latin artists including Colombian singer [[Maluma (singer)|Maluma]].<ref name=protest/> J Balvin's campaign was launched shortly after cancelling his performance on Miss USA 2015 in protest of Donald Trump.<ref name=protest/> He supports [[LGBT]] rights, explaining \"It\u2019s all about love. A lot of my closest friends are gay\", and dyed his hair rainbow colors to show support for [[Pride parade|Pride]] 2019.<ref name=throughhell>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2019/jul/27/j-balvin-on-breakdowns-escobar-and-beyonce-reggaeton|title=\u2018I\u2019ve been through hell\u2019: J Balvin on breakdowns, Escobar and Beyonc\u00e9|work=The Guardian|date=July 27, 2019|accessdate=March 24, 2020|last=Collins|first=Hattie}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2016, the singer was involved in a plane crash while leaving the Bahamas.<ref name=scary>{{cite news|url=http://www.foxnews.com/entertainment/2016/08/29/scary-j-balvin-survives-plane-crash-in-bahamas-calls-it-miracle.html|title=J Balvin survives plane crash in Bahamas, calls it 'a miracle'|work=Fox News|publisher=Fox Entertainment Group|date=August 29, 2016|accessdate=March 30, 2018}}</ref><ref name=survives>{{cite news|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/latin/7487846/j-balvin-survives-airplane-crash-scare-bahamas|title=J Balvin Survives Airplane Crash Scare, Rep Confirms|work=Billboard|publisher=Prometheus Global Media|date=August 26, 2016|accessdate=March 30, 2018}}</ref> While returning from a vacation with his family, the plane failed to take off properly and crash landed shortly after departing from the runway.<ref name=accidente>{{cite news|url=http://cnnespanol.cnn.com/2016/08/26/j-balvin-sufre-accidente-aereo-en-una-avioneta-en-bahamas/|title=J Balvin sufre accidente a\u00e9reo en una avioneta en Bahamas|work=CNN en Espa\u00f1ol|date=August 26, 2016|accessdate=March 30, 2018|publisher=CNN Corporation}}</ref> He posted a photo on Instagram of the small private plane after having landed in the bushes. Nobody was injured in the accident, and J Balvin called it \"a miracle.\"<ref name=scary/>\n\nJ Balvin experiences [[panic attacks]] and states that \"meditation saved [his] life\".<ref name=throughhell/> When his anxiety was at its worst, he recalled that \u201cI forgot about my happiness. I forgot about Jos\u00e9 (J Balvin's given name).\u201d<ref name=reasonstolove>{{cite web|url=http://people.com/chica/5-reasons-to-love-mi-gente-singer-j-balvin/|title=5 Reasons to Love 'Mi Gente' Singer J Balvin|work=People|last=Hansen|first=Lena|date=October 27, 2017|accessdate=March 30, 2018}}</ref> He is known for his tattoos and got his first tattoo when he was twelve years old.<ref name=gqtattoo>{{cite web|url=http://video.gq.com/watch/j-balvin-got-his-first-tattoo-when-he-was-12|title=Tattoo Tour - J Balvin|work=GQ|publisher=Cond\u00e9 Nast|date=March 20, 2018|accessdate=March 30, 2018}}</ref> His mother suffers from the rare genetic condition [[acute intermittent porphyria]], which causes seizures, chronic pain, and mental health difficulties. He has the word \"Familia\" tattooed on his chest in her honor.<ref name=reasonstolove/>\n\nUnlike many popular reggaeton singers who move to the United States upon gaining popularity, J Balvin continues to live in his hometown of Medellin, explaining, \"It keeps me real. I'm gonna be real everywhere I go, but I'm with my people, I'm connected to my roots \u2013 I'm in my country! I don't need to live somewhere else. I respect the ones who make it and leave their home base, but I'm good in Colombia.\".<ref name=nirvana/>\n\n== Discography ==\n{{Main|J Balvin discography}}\n* ''[[Real (album)|Real]]'' (2009)\n* ''[[La Familia (album)|La Familia]]'' (2013)\n* ''[[Energia (album)|Energ\u00eda]]'' (2016)\n* ''[[Vibras (album)|Vibras]]'' (2018)\n* ''[[Oasis (J Balvin and Bad Bunny album)|Oasis]]'' {{small|(with [[Bad Bunny]])}} (2019)\n* ''[[Colores]]'' (2020)\n\n==Tours==\n===Headlining===\n*La Familia Tour with [[Becky G]] (2015)\n*[[Energia (album)#Energia Tour|Energ\u00eda Tour]] (2016\u20132018)\n*[[Vibras Tour]] (2018)\n*[[Arcoiris Tour]] (2019)\n\n===Supporting===\n*[[The Sun Comes Out World Tour]] (2011)\n*[[Sex and Love Tour]] (2014)\n\n==Awards and nominations==\n{{Main|List of awards and nominations received by J Balvin}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|J Balvin}}\n*{{Official website|http://jbalvin.com/}}\n\n{{Portal bar|Biography|Colombia|Latin music}}\n{{J Balvin}}\n{{Lo Nuestro Award for Artist of the Year |state=collapsed}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Balvin, J.}}\n[[Category:1985 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Capitol Latin artists]]\n[[Category:Colombian artists]]\n[[Category:Colombian hip hop musicians]]\n[[Category:Colombian male singers]]\n[[Category:Colombian reggaeton artists]]\n[[Category:Latin Grammy Award winners]]\n[[Category:Latin music songwriters]]\n[[Category:Latin pop musicians]]\n[[Category:MTV EMA winners]]\n[[Category:People from Medell\u00edn]]\n[[Category:Universal Music Latin Entertainment artists]]\n[[Category:Urbano musicians]]\n", "name_user": "UnderKid504-2", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eDiscography", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/J_Balvin"}
{"title_page": "Gymnastics at the 2002 West Asian Games", "text_new": "{{Infobox sports competition event\n| event       = Gymnastics\n| games       = 2002 West Asian Games\n| image       = Gymnastics (artistic) pictogram.svg\n| image_size  = 100px\n| venue       = Yarmouk Hall\n| date        = 10\u201312 April\n| prev        = \n| next        = [[Gymnastics at the 2005 West Asian Games|2005]]\n}}\n'''[[Artistic gymnastics]]''' at the [[2002 West Asian Games]] was held at Yarmouk Hall, [[Kuwait City]], [[Kuwait]] from 10 April 2002 to 12 April 2002.<ref>{{cite web |title=\u0645\u0633\u0643 \u0627\u0644\u062e\u062a\u0627\u0645 \u0644\u0623\u0628\u0637\u0627\u0644 \u0627\u0644\u0643\u0648\u064a\u062a \u0641\u064a \u0627\u0644\u062c\u0645\u0628\u0627\u0632 |url=http://www.alazraq.com/parts/show.php?page=article.php&a_id=23873 |publisher=alazraq.com |accessdate=31 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nIt had a men's only programme containing 8 events. A total of 6 nations (Iran, Syria, Kuwait, Saudi Arabia, Jordan and Yemen) participated.\n\n==Medalists==\n{|{{MedalistTable|type=Event}}\n|-\n|Team\n|{{flagIOC2|KUW|2002 West Asian Games}}<br />[[Ahmad Al-Duraia]]<br />[[Fahad Al-Ghannam]]<br />[[Ahmad Al-Herz]]<br />[[Saqer Al-Mulla]]<br />[[Mohammad Al-Omran]]<br />[[Nayef Dashti]]<br />[[Bader Mohammad]]\n|{{flagIOC2|IRI|2002 West Asian Games}}<br />[[Mahmoud Arab]]<br />[[Mahan Bajrang]]<br />[[Mohammad Hadi Ghasemi]]<br />[[Ahmad Majdi]]<br />[[Mehdi Niroumand]]<br />[[Mohammad Reza Samaei]]<br />[[Ali Shariati (gymnast)|Ali Shariati]]\n|valign=top|{{flagIOC2|SYR|2002 West Asian Games}}<br />[[Ahmad Amir Abdulkafi]]<br />[[Louay Al-Heraki]]<br />[[Amer Attar]]<br />[[Fadi Bahlawan]]<br />[[Mohammad Daher]]<br />[[Sadeq Daher]]\n|-\n|rowspan=2|Individual all-around\n|rowspan=2|{{flagIOC2medalist|[[Saqer Al-Mulla]]|KUW|2002 West Asian Games}}\n|{{flagIOC2medalist|[[Mohammad Hadi Ghasemi]]|IRI|2002 West Asian Games}}\n|rowspan=2|''Shared silver''\n|-\n|{{flagIOC2medalist|[[Fadi Bahlawa